      <text>Your friendly RAS MoN here... I ran across something the other day, and
I wanted to point it out, jot it down for the general populous to note
as well. In book 6, there is a very specific and very appopriate reference
to the behavior of Aes Sedai. You all remember Nynaeve's habit of the
incessant braid-tugging, right? Seems harmless enough. Well, this is
what one of the Blue sisters had to say about it (and this happens in
Salidar, as well, so it IS applicable to all) --- Lelaine eyed Nynaeve's
hand on her braid, and she snatched it away. Too many knew about that habit,
a habit she had tried hard to break. But what the Aes Sedai said was &quot;Not
when it impinges on the dignity of Aes Sedai, child. Women who serve Aes
Sedai should show some reserve in public, however silly they are in private.&quot;
There was nothing to be said to that. Nothing safe, anyway.
 
That's RJ's take on it, guys and gals... Straightforward, to the point,
and it covers a multitude of bases. I post this because this applies not
only to Novices and Accepted, but to Aes Sedai. Shawl-wearers aren't just
about ordering people around and acting snooty... It's about dignity,
respect, and the honor of the sisterhood is taken to a personal level.
All Ajahs, all matters, all the time ;)
 
That is all, carry on.
 
Rosabelle, Lio, et al
</text>
    </message>
